 transformed the lives of young people. He then widens the lens to describe a history of imperialism and corruption that shaped this underworld—from Cold War counterinsurgency to the “War on Drugs” to the near-impunity of white-collar crime—as he follows local gangs who embrace new trades in the illicit economy. Carter describes the gangs’ transformation from neighborhood groups to sprawling criminal societies, even in the National Penitentiary, where they have become political as much as criminal communities. Gothic Sovereignty reveals not only how the revolutionary potential of gangs was lost when they merged with powerful cartels but also how close analysis of criminal communities enables profound reflection on the economic, legal, and existential discontents of globalization in late liberal nation-states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCartelszHondurasxHistory. 0aGangsxPolitical aspectszHondurasxHistory. 0aGangszHondurasxHistory. 0aGangszHondurasxSocial life and customs. 0aPolice corruptionxSocial aspectszHonduras. 0aTattooingzHonduras. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aHonduras, cartel violence, cartel, gangs, anthropology, undocumented migrants, social theory, Central America, ethnography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477324172423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477324172/original  a978-3-11-076651-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK